[3] Rabies, bovine, human exposure - Texas
Date: 26 Jul 2012
Source: KXII.com [summ., edited]
http://www.kxii.com/home/misc/Grayson-Co-confirmed-case-of-rabies-in-cow-163835126.html


Grayson Co. confirmed case of rabies in cow

A show cow in Grayson County tested positive for rabies near the end of June. Rabies is a viral disease that attacks the central nervous system and is rarely ever seen in cows.

Each year, the Texas Department of State Health Services reports the number of animals tested for rabies. Of the state's 232 counties listed last year, only nine counties had rabid bovine including Grayson.

Texas Department of State Health Services out of Arlington notified Grayson County Health about the infected cow just a few weeks ago.

The show heffer was a beloved family pet from southwest Grayson County.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promd@promedmail.org>

[Texas may be found on the interactive Healthmap at: http://healthmap.org/r/2XCN.

In all likelihood this bovine pet caused human exposure.

If there are show animals, whether the animal is bovine, or horse or other animals, it is important to vaccinate these animals against rabies. We are around these animals all the time, this is a protection for our animals and especially for ourselves.

Vaccinating your pets, regardless of their size is cheap insurance to help protect your life and the life of your pet.

Most large animals (horses, cattle, goats etc) are curious animals. So when a skunk or raccoon or some other rabid animal is in the pasture, the farm animal will go and investigate this strange creature in their habitat. The animal puts its nose down to investigate this odd visitor and receives a bite on the nose for its trouble. We may not notice the bite, and certainly if this occurs at night, we may never see the rabid animal. Nevertheless, our pet has been exposed to rabies, and may expose us.

Please vaccinate your pets, your horses and yes your show animals. - Mod.TG]
